[2026-07-04] PATTERN NOTE — credentials leaking via raw log calls
Second occurrence in Wave 2: 1B's PubMed client leaked NCBI_API_KEY/
NCBI_EMAIL via an uncaught httpx exception's URL-embedded message on
4xx responses; 1C's OAuth handshake leaked raw Zotero oauth_token/
oauth_token_secret via `logger.exception("...: %r", tokens)` on a
malformed access-token response. Both are the same underlying failure
mode — an error/exception path that logs a raw object/exception
containing live secrets instead of a sanitized summary — independently
introduced by the same specialist in two different files, each caught
only by adversarial-generalist's review, not by the specialist's own
tests or tester's checkpoint. Recommend Task 3D (cross-cutting
middleware, §10.3/§10.5/§10.7 — the catch-all exception handler) adopt
a project-wide rule/lint check against logging raw request/response
objects, request URLs with query params, or `%r`-formatted external
API payloads, rather than relying on adversarial review to catch each
instance ad hoc. Flagging forward to Task 3D's brief.

